 Premiere Academy, Lugbe, Abuja, has appealed to the public to shun rumours and wait for the police to unravel how Keren-Happuch Akpagher, a 14-year-old pupil of the institution, died. The school said the autopsy report on the girl’s death was not out yet , adding that no report has indicted the school. Acting Principal of the school Chris Akinsowon said  a team of pathologists led by the police started their investigation on Wednesday, July 7. The SS1 pupil, Karen-Happuch, was alleged to have been sexually abused before she was withdrawn from the school by her mother, Mrs Vihimga Akpagher, on June 19, 2021, for treatment. Karen-Happuch, however, died two days later in hospital in the Wuse 2 area of Abuja. According to the principal, the process will likely take some weeks before the result will be out. He also expressed concerns that some groups have taken it upon themselves to spread fake news on the death of the student.  He appealed to Nigerians to wait for the autopsy result and the police investigation. He said the school has also started its own investigation into the incident. Capital territory police commissioner Bala Ciroma said discreet investigation is ongoing to unravel the circumstances that led to the death of the 14-year-old. Ciroma pledged that the police would be professional, fair and thorough in the investig A statement issued by the FCT Police Public Relations Officer, ASP Yusuf Mariam, said: “Following the incident of alleged rape of one Karen-Happuch Akpagher ‘f’ 14 years now deceased, a student of Premier Academy, Lugbe, the command wishes to state categorically that discreet investigation is still ongoing. “Hence, the Commissioner of Police CP. Bala Ciroma wishes to reassure members of the public that the Command will be professional, fair and thorough in its investigation. Furthermore, the Command urges Abuja residents to remain calm and allow the law to take its cause”. 